{"guideId":"baf481a9-ae65-416a-a500-3b87fc19cf04","chunks":[{"content":"Database Lab Spring 2026 Lab 05 – Week 05 MySQL Queries DCL (Data Control Language) is used to control access to data stored in the database. It manages: • Who can access the database • What operations they can perform • On which objects (tables, views, etc.) Main DCL Commands Command Purpose GRANT Gives privileges to a user REVOKE Removes privileges from a user System Privileges Allow users to perform database-level operations. Examples: • CREATE TABLE • CREATE VIEW • CREATE USER • DROP DATABASE Object Privileges Allow users to perform operations on specific objects. Examples: • SELECT • INSERT • UPDATE • DELETE -- 1 of 5 -- Sequence for DCL (Step-by-Step Flow) Step 1: Login as Admin Because only admin (or user with privilege) can: • Create database • Create tables • Create users • Grant privileges Step 2: Create Database Step 3: Create Objects (Tables) Step 4: Insert Sample Data Step 5: Create Users Examples: CREATE USER 'hr_user'@'localhost' IDENTIFIED BY 'hr123'; CREATE USER 'manager_user'@'localhost' IDENTIFIED BY 'manager123'; Step 6: Grant Object Privileges Example: GRANT SELECT ON company_db.Employees TO 'hr_user'@'localhost'; STEP 7: Create New Connection (Very Important) In MySQL Workbench: 1. Click ➕ (New Connection) 2. Connection Name: Intern_User 3. Username: intern_user 4. Store Password: intern123 5. Test Connection 6. Save Now open THIS connection (not root). STEP 8: Validate the GRANT SELECT CURRENT_USER(); Test Allowed Operation (Should Work) SELECT * FROM company_db.Employees; Test Unauthorized Operation (Should Fail) INSERT INTO company_db.Employees VALUES (3, 'Hina', 45000, 'HR'); Revoke Privilege Syntax: REVOKE privilege_type ON database_name.object_name FROM 'username'@'host'; -- 2 of 5 -- Transactions : A sequence of one or more SQL operations (queries) that are executed as a single unit of work. • Either all operations succeed, or none of them do. • Ensures data integrity in the database. Properties of Transactions (ACID) 1. Atomicity – All or nothing (either the whole transaction happens or nothing happens) 2. Consistency – Database moves from one valid state to another valid state 3. Isolation – Transactions do not interfere with each other 4. Durability – Once committed, changes are permanent Mnemonic: A-C-I-D → think of database as “acid test” for integrity Basic Transaction Commands in SQL Command Purpose START TRANSACTION / BEGIN Begin a transaction COMMIT Save all changes permanently ROLLBACK Undo changes since transaction started Step 1: Start Transaction START TRANSACTION; Step 2: Perform Operations UPDATE Employees SET salary = salary + 5000 WHERE emp_id = 1; UPDATE Employees SET salary = salary - 5000 WHERE emp_id = 2; Step 3: Commit or Rollback If everything is correct , then “ COMMIT”. Otherwise, “ ROLLBACK” What is Savepoint? A SAVEPOINT is a marker inside a transaction that allows you to rollback to a specific point instead of undoing the entire transaction. Introduction to Procedural Programming in Databases Procedural programming allows you to write SQL statements in a structured, logical way, combining control structures like conditions, loops, and functions. Unlike simple SQL queries, procedural programming helps you perform complex operations, repeat tasks,","embedding":[-0.038687556982040405,0.01745416410267353,-0.07622133195400238,0.03450888767838478,-0.10322186350822449,-0.030628863722085953,0.044625621289014816,-0.02634895220398903,0.010682712309062481,0.04182076081633568,0.05834806337952614,-0.023042015731334686,0.11009962111711502,-0.042511940002441406,-0.013644853606820107,0.0701536014676094,0.055153194814920425,-0.012460911646485329,-0.11094578355550766,-0.0026456001214683056,0.027657970786094666,-0.0873502865433693,-0.06371914595365524,0.010488534346222878,-0.017014678567647934,-0.05109517276287079,-0.015956943854689598,0.008892709389328957,-0.023418938741087914,-0.05542409047484398,-0.0565788708627224,