cks depending on the situation. Loops (FOR, WHILE) Purpose Loops allow you to repeat a block of code multiple times until a condition is met. Useful for processing multiple rows or repeating calculations. Types of Loops Loop Type Description FOR Loop Executes a fixed number of times WHILE Loop Executes until a condition becomes false LOOP / EXIT WHEN General loop with manual exit condition Functions Purpose Functions are named blocks of code that: • Perform a specific task • Return a single value • Can be reused in queries or inside procedures Tasks: You are required to configure database access for different users in a company database. Each user has specific responsibilities and should be granted only the permissions necessary for their role. You must: 1. Create a database called Company_Database and table called Employees & Departments. 2. Insert 5 Columns and 5 records in the table. 3. Create the following users with passwords: 4. HR_User 5. Intern_User 6. Admin_User The following users require access: 7. HR_User → Can view and update employee & department records. 8. Intern_User → Can only view employee records. -- 4 of 5 -- 9. Admin_User → Has full control over the database. Task 1: Log in as HR_User and write a query to generate a report that displays: • The name of each department • The total number of employees working in that department • The average salary of employees in that department Task 2: Log in as a Intern_User, update the salary of an employee who doesn’t have any department. Task 3: Revoke the Update privilege from HR_User and execute the first task again. Task 4: Log in as Admin_User. Begin a transaction before making any changes. Write a DELETE query using a subquery to remove employees in departments where all salaries are ≤ 50,000. Preview the changes using a SELECT statement. Commit the transaction if the results are correct, otherwise rollback. Task 5: Create a table named Employee_Bonus with the following columns: • emp_id → INT, primary key, references Employees(emp_id) • performance_score → INT • bonus_amount → DECIMAL(10,2) Insert at least 5 sample records with random performance scores (1–10) and NULL for bonus_amount. Update Bonus Using Procedural Programming: Write a function named calculate_bonus that: • Takes performance_score as input • Returns the bonus amount according to the rules: Performance Score Bonus Amount 9–10 1000 7–8 500 5–6 200 <5 0 • Loop through all records in Employee_Bonus. • Use the calculate_bonus function to update the bonus_amount for each employee.","embedding":[-0.027383100241422653,0.06016579642891884,-0.07735399901866913,-0.0005942858406342566,-0.1217237338423729,-0.06757573783397675,0.039869338274002075,0.028317563235759735,-0.057414811104536057,0.08625739067792892,0.051928773522377014,0.006494293920695782,0.0832749605178833,-0.0660649836063385,-0.056305162608623505,0.0381130613386631,-0.022319374606013298,0.04209836199879646,-0.03851045295596123,-0.03512631729245186,0.04121081531047821,-0.04200435057282448,-0.03494134917855263,0.040313370525836945,-0.016397610306739807,-0.029401050880551338,0.044680915772914886,0.0127794174477458,-0.11294518411159515,-0.04097338765859604,-0.045317016541957855,0.0013765398180112243,0.04781680554151535,0.03339152783155441,0.012447400018572807,-0.06446648389101028,0.028699658811092377,0.01219092682003975,0.02110075019299984,0.009148459881544113,-0.10371670871973038,-0.015364432707428932,-0.011914537288248539,-0.03591643646359444,-0.019780227914452553,-0.021709656342864037,-0.1396091729402542,-0.012624048627912998,0.009810182265937328,0.016052229329943657,-0.043068777769804,-0.010002285242080688,-0.00862217042595148,0.024557141587138176,0.029819030314683914,-0.0572836734354496,0.07243190705776215,-0.04423990845680237,-0.07816576212644577,-0.062218885868787766,-0.0129745714366436,0.06532169133424759,0.007438429165631533,-0.02235088311135769,0.04116113483905792,0.008098171092569828,-0.042410049587488174,-0.02807060070335865,0.0260348301